<div class="comm-preview-panel description-panel"><p>The community team bridges the Project with its primary stakeholders, maintaining close partnerships with the community and the LGU of the 50 sites. They conduct research on community risk and response, EWS-L framework and infrastructure, and organization development.</p><br><p>CT facilitates trainings and seminars to build capacities of the community, and meets and consults with LGUs, all to forward the effective implementation of a people-centered early warning system for landslides (EWS-L).
</p></div>

<div class="data-preview-panel description-panel"><p>The monitoring team is the primary thrust of the Dynaslope Project in conducting the research and development of threshold and forecasting models for the early warning system of landslides. The team studies and analyzes the current and historical data pool of the project from a multitude of sources to create accurate and data driven threshold models through a peer reviewed scientific process.</p>
<br>
<p>The team also acts as a support to the implementation of the early warning system protocol by developing codes for the automated generation of triggers and alert evaluation. The team also conducts a regular review of the current protocol prior to the formulation and proposition of revisions geared towards an efficient day to day operations and a thoroughgoing early warning system in order for accurate and informative alerts to be disseminated to the community ensuring the safety and awareness of every stakeholder."</p><br><p>The Survey Squad is responsible for the in-depth characterization of the landslide hazard present in the monitoring sites. The team carries out several field surveys in order to map the landslide hazard. Analysis of the landslide features, material, and monitoring data were then conducted to identify the households and other structures at risk to the landslide hazard.</p></div>

